{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a4a30cd-5495-4aab-948d-790cea4b9480","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project itself is clean — the slowness isn't from the `.csproj` configuration. The developer report confirms the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps a long-lived MSBuild process in memory.\n\nHere are the concrete fixes, ordered by impact:\n\n### 1. Skip restore on incremental builds\nThe quickest win — NuGet restore runs every time by default:\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nRun `dotnet restore` once, then use `--no-restore` for subsequent builds.\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server (**.NET 8+**)\nThis keeps a long-lived MSBuild process warm between CLI invocations — the same strategy VS uses:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr set it project-wide in `Directory.Build.props`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseMSBuildServer>true</UseMSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### 3. Use `dotnet watch` for edit-build-test loops\nEliminates cold-start entirely by watching for file changes:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 4. Enable terminal logger suppression (minor)\nThe default terminal logger adds overhead:\n```bash\ndotnet build -tl:off\n```\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation:** Options **1 + 2** together will bring CLI incremental builds close to VS performance. Add `--no-restore` to your build alias and set `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` in your shell profile. For rapid iteration, use `dotnet watch`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e0ecfa7-2d55-4a3f-aa0a-377bbc74fa22","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses the MSBuild Server (a long-lived process that keeps the MSBuild engine warm), which avoids the overhead of:\n1. Starting a new .NET process\n2. JIT-compiling MSBuild assemblies\n3. Re-evaluating the project graph from scratch\n\nThe solution is to enable the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild build server or `dotnet build-server`) for CLI builds. \n\nThis feature became available in .NET 8. The most practical fixes are enabling the MSBuild Server via the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable or setting `<UseMSBuildServer>true</UseMSBuildServer>` in the project file to keep MSBuild warm between builds, using `dotnet build --no-restore` to skip NuGet restore when dependencies haven't changed, and leveraging `dotnet watch` during development to maintain a persistent process that only rebuilds on file changes.","outputTokens":1034},"id":"51e46d9d-76d7-4c7e-a4c4-17f6935ddc2e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:29.267Z","parentId":"083ddf26-32d9-43e8-bd9f-55063a6240e8"}
